Certain <h> commands allow you to send ANSI color codes to others set
up to properly interpret them.  This is done by entering a replacement string
that will be changed to the equivalent color string.  To do this, surround the
color character with < and >.   

  <<<r>)  <r>RED<z>       <<<R>)<R> BOLD RED<z>       <<<b>) <b>BLUE<z>      <<<B>) <B>BOLD BLUE<z> 
  <<<g>)  <g>GREEN<z>     <<<G>)<G> BOLD GREEN<z>     <<<c>) <c>CYAN<z>      <<<C>) <C>BOLD CYAN<z>
  <<<p>)  <p>PURPLE<z>    <<<P>) <P>BOLD PURPLE<z>    <O/o>) <o>ORANGE<z>  <Y/y>) <y>YELLOW<z>
  <<<k>)   <k>GRAY<z>     <<<K>) <K>BLACK<z>          <<<w>) <w>WHITE<1>     <<<W>) <W>BOLD WHITE<z>
  <D/d>) <d>BOLD<z>     <I/i>) <i>INVERT<z>       <Z/z/1>) TERMINATE/NORMAL

  n/N) your name
    * - for notes/mail/etc., this will be the name of the reader.

  Note: to actually show a < character, type it three times.  e.g. <<<<<1> for <<<1>

IMMORTAL ONLY:

  <F/f>)  <f>FLASHING<z>       <E/e>)  <e>BLACK_ON_WHITE<z>   <J/j>)  <j>BLACK_ON_BLACK<z>
  <L/l>)  <l>WHITE_ON_RED<z>   <Q/q>)  <q>WHITE_ON_GREEN<z>   <T/t>)  <t>WHITE_ON_ORANGE<z> 
  <U/u>)  <u>WHITE_ON_BLUE<z>  <V/v>)  <v>WHITE_ON_PURPLE<z>  <x/X>)  <x>WHITE_ON_CYAN<z>


For example :
    say I am a <<<b>fuzzy<<<z> <<<W>bunny!<<<1>
    would cause you to say "I am a <b>fuzzy<z> <W>bunny!<1>"

Abuse of color codes to annoy or harass others will probably lead to
limitations being put into effect.  Let's all play nice and not try to 
blind each other.  Long descriptions of simple objects should be one color
or white.  Short descriptions should generally not be more than 2 colors
and white.   Rooms should not be rainbows nor should most objects unless
it really makes sense.  If you use a color word in the object like
a red potion, make the object red.

Note: The yellow and orange codes are actually identical.  Certain ANSI capable
interpreters will display it one way, others in the other way.

Note: Be careful in the use of bold (% D/d).  You *will* need to terminate it
if you want a non bold color to follow.

Note: The quality of ANSI displays depends heavily on communication and
terminal software.  Not all programs support the full range of Ansi options
(eg. red and red-bold appear identical).

See Also: COLOR
